The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 NHPC flotation gets green signal

 OUR CORRESPONDENT

 New Delhi, Dec. 7: The government today gave a go-ahead to National Hydroelectric Power Corporation for an initial public offer (IPO) of up to 24 per cent of its share capital, a move that would help the public sector unit in attaining its Rs 30,000-crore investment plans by 2012.

 The decision to allow NHPC to raise money from domestic and external markets was taken at a meeting of the cabinet committee on economic affairs, chaired by Prime Minister Manmohan Singh here.

 Announcing the decision, information and broadcasting minister P.R. Das Munshi said: CCEA gave its approval to allow NHPC to go for an IPO not exceeding 24 per cent of its share capital in one or more tranches from domestic and external markets.

 Asked about the timing of IPO, he said, as soon as possible.

 The approval to NHPC comes just two weeks after the CCEA allowed three other power sector PSUs PFC, PowerGrid and Rural Electrification Corporation to tap the capital market.

 When contacted, NHPC chairman S.K. Garg said, the decision augurs well for the corporation.

 NHPC, with a share capital of Rs 10,349 crore, would be able to offer shares worth up to Rs 2,500 crore at a premium. The company has an authorised capital of Rs 15,000 crore.

 Limited liability bill

 The Union cabinet today approved the introduction of limited liability partnership (LLP) bill in the ongoing winter session of Parliament. The bill will facilitate in creating other business model which will enable growth in the economy, Das Munshi said.

 The cabinet also approved a financial restructuring of Bharat Pumps and Compressors Ltd by writing off over Rs 150 crore debt.




